In this section, we shall compare losses due to friction in four metallic pipes: cast iron, stainless steel, galvanized steel, and copper. The pipe is 5 m long and has an inner diameter of 4 cm, while keeping the flow between 80 L/min to 120 L/min. The idea is to cross-compare theoretical and experimental data, analyze the role of the metal on losses and check purely in simulation models. These figures are ready to show the experimental and theoretical data for each of the metals separately, with their error percentage. We use this to show robustness of the experimental results and compare them with mathematical models. Figure 2 presents the experimental investigation and theoretical results estimated relationship between flow rate and head loses (
h f
) for the four pipes of different metals.

